  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Achieving and sustaining greater access to education in Beaufort West</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Beaufort West in South Africa experiences high levels of poverty, violence, substance abuse and HIV/Aids. Many children have experienced neglect or abuse at home, school or on the street. Without the ability to cope and without appropriate support from parents, teachers and community members, many children drop out of school, unable to return. This project will help 154 children back into mainstream education and prevent school dropout for 300 at-risk children. It will support children and parents through befriending street-involved children, family liaison, and developing children and parents&#x2019; coping skills and self-esteem. Literacy and numeracy needs and reinsertion into mainstream school will be supported through eight community-based informal home-schools. Workshops will be held for parents and children on HIV/Aids, drug prevention and parenting skills and ten families in most need will receive therapeutic support. 100 teachers will receive training on effectively addressing children&#x2019;s needs ensuring sustained attendance for those that have returned to school and reduced drop-out for those at risk. Sustainability will be enhanced by dialogue with regional representations of the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Social Development, to ensure that existing policy is implemented in line with community needs.</narrative>
  </description>
